{#
  Helm values for Longhorn storage.

  Variables:
    longhorn_replica_count: Number of volume replicas. Set dynamically to match the
                            cluster node count at deployment time.

  LOAD-BEARING — DO NOT LOWER engineReplicaTimeout OR
  replicaReplenishmentWaitInterval BACK TO DEFAULTS. These are tuned up
  from Longhorn defaults (8s and 600s) to prevent the auto-salvage +
  cross-node-rebuild cascade that happens whenever every node's
  instance-manager restarts simultaneously — which is the normal case for
  cluster-wide suspend/resume, coordinated reboot, and dirty power loss.
  Symptoms of the cascade (observed and fixed):
    - EXT4-fs "shut down requested (2)" on iSCSI sd* devices in dmesg
    - JBD2 I/O error when updating journal superblock
    - tens of GB of cross-node rebuild traffic per cycle
  The short defaults mark all replicas Failed the moment managers restart,
  which triggers auto-salvage and a detach-during-rebuild step that aborts
  ext4 journals on top of the volumes. The longer timeouts give replicas
  time to reconnect cleanly before anything declares them failed, and the
  longer replenishment interval means that if a replica IS briefly marked
  Failed, Longhorn waits 30 minutes before kicking off a new-replica
  rebuild — well past any expected suspend window. engineReplicaTimeout is
  set to 300s (5 min) because empirical timing shows instance-manager takes
  ~95s+ after kubelet start to be fully ready; the 30s default was too
  short and still triggered rebuilds (observed 2026-04-22).
#}
defaultSettings:
  defaultDataPath: /var/lib/longhorn
  storageReservedPercentageForDefaultDisk: 30
  storageMinimalAvailablePercentage: 25
  storageOverProvisioningPercentage: 100
  engineReplicaTimeout: 300
  replicaReplenishmentWaitInterval: 1800
persistence:
  defaultClassReplicaCount: {{ longhorn_replica_count }}
  defaultClass: true
